    cellular: { title: "Sinusitis Treatment Approach", content: "Sinusitis management requires distinguishing viral rhinosinusitis (90% of cases) from acute bacterial rhinosinusitis (ABRS, ~2-10%) to avoid unnecessary antibiotic prescribing. Viral sinusitis is self-limited (7-10 days) and managed with supportive care. ABRS is diagnosed clinically when symptoms persist ≥10 days without improvement (persistent), worsen after initial improvement (double worsening/biphasic), or present with severe onset (high fever ≥39°C + purulent nasal discharge ≥3 consecutive days). First-line antibiotic for ABRS is amoxicillin-clavulanate 875/125 mg BID × 5-7 days (IDSA guidelines). High-dose amoxicillin-clavulanate (2g/125 mg BID) for regions with high penicillin-resistant S. pneumoniae (>10%). Doxycycline is the alternative for penicillin-allergic patients (NOT azithromycin — high resistance rates). Chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS, symptoms >12 weeks) is subdivided into CRS with nasal polyps (CRSwNP — eosinophilic inflammation, treat with intranasal steroids + biologics if severe) and CRS without polyps (CRSsNP — mixed inflammation). Imaging (CT sinus) is NOT indicated for acute sinusitis unless complications are suspected. CT is the gold standard for chronic sinusitis and surgical planning." },
